presidents, nnd A.\nChen cashier.\nWalker's Copper Letter.\nWalls- r's t \"upper belter in Sat urda v\ni 11 t n 11 untneroia I will say: t'opp r i;\nqiii t .in.2 a shad** easier in Ion Duke\nis 1'. rents and electrolytic is 1- t to\n,.4.iiIs per pound. Sales of lake in 100.0M;\nand jM'.ecd pound lets were made Monday\nat rents f* r July delivery. The kir;\nt Him; art la is holding its price for\nrt, 11 idyl i at i:{ rents, and its attitude\niii thi. i' pert is doin-. more than al\nls, o t anything else to sustain j\u00bbr it*\nOtIn r s.-ll is of rl rtiolytir are offerin';\nand disposing: of all their output *|uit<*\nreadily at l~;ji t*> 1 JTs .cents.\nThe imreasc of IS. Ml.Ml pounds in the\n;n <simulated surplus, shown hy the\nport of the (\\\u00bbpner Producers' ass iati'Ui.\nwas a sever** disappointment to the min\nim; interests. Th** figures were in a\nmeasure a. repetition of those the pre\nceding month, the increase in produc\ntion. r\u00bb.7'd,V7 pounds, bring almost evenly\nhalan.-ed hv the f*. lvd.r,<p pounds increase\nin deliveries. The growth of the surplus\nis beginning; to suggest that the copper\nmin* of America ate now producing\nabout pounds more monthly\nthan they should. So sensitive is 111\nmetal inatinn that when production falls\nonly .V low rnnsumpt ion rcjuii '-ment s\nprices soar. hut. on the other hand, a .Vi\ns of production always brings cx\nti- mc depression to the trade.\nProduction continues to increase; and\nnow that new railroad financing in this\nom1tr\\ has been tied up indetinit* Iv. it\ncI\u2022 not se.-m probable that tlm domestic\nr i\u2022nsumptioii of can show much of\nan increase during the remainder of the\nyear. Tl*e deevease of T.TV^.eiiO pounds in\nthe foreign visible supples during May\noffs t in part the gain in accumulated\nstocks of copper in this country. Kuro\npeaii oasumpt on will probably eontinip*\nto inereosp. and this- may eoioit'Thelan*-\"\nthe depression in this country. At the\nmoment th-* outlook for the metal mar\nhat pres* nts little that is encouraging.\nDIED.\nPVPrett. Mass -Juno V, Anson <1\nSt a m -hli. I'1. !'orili*i!\\ of I I a Howell, Me.,\nin his sstii year, bowdoin t\u2019allege. class\nof 1v 17. Funeral service will he held at\nM hroadway, Kverett. Mass, on Sun\nlay. June 1 at I*. M. Kclatives and\nft: unis are invited to attend.\nGet One And Be Glad*\nOn Every Baking Bay\nThe Range that Makes Cooking Easy\u2019\nTaber Reid, Augusta\nrragw; \"AlftTTWBMnMWMWnBMiaMM\n\nTRADE REVIEW.\nBusiness Outlook Better\nThen for Last Week.\nMore Fall Orders lor Foot\nwear in New England,\nFailures Somewhat Less Than for\nCorresponding Week, 1909.\nNew York, Juno 10.- R. <1. Dun\nCo\u2019s. Weekly Review of Trade tomor\nrow will say:\nWith a compromise effected on the\nquestion of railroad rates which,\nthough depending in part on action by\nCongress on the railroad bills, is re\ngarded as satisfactory; and with crop\nprospects for both wheat atu| cotton\ndecidedly good, the business outlook\nshows much improvement over last\nweek. The improvement is largely\nsentimental, hut increased confidence\nalmost invariably leads to increased\ntrade.\nFormal notice from the largest pro\nducers of cotton and woolen goods of\nan intention to curtail production very\nmaterially bespeaks the difficulties be\nsetting textile lines as a consequence\nof the sub-normal demand and the\nI ires sure upon costs induced by t lie\nhigh it ml uncertain values on raw ma\nterials. Jobbers still pursue a hand\nto mouth policy in buying, and selling\nagents await expected indications of\nan early broadening in the call for\nmerchandise. Manufacturers are pur\nchasing in a limited way and there is\nsome increase in the call for staple do\nmestics. while the miscellaneous trade\nis quiet but fairly steady.\nTrade in footwear continues quiet\nand manufacturers throughout New\nEngland are running under materially\nreduced headway hut slight improve\nment is noticeable as New England\nmanufacturers arc getting in more fall\norders. Current orders are still back\nward. 1 ,eatiler is decidedly dull. Hem\nlock dry hide sole is fairly steady, but\nthere is considerable weakness in oak\nand union sole and most kinds of up\nper leather and lower. Prices of hem\nlock tannages of harness leather are\nchiefly affected and from one to three\ncents lower.\nDullness and weakness characterize\nthe hide market and prices are lower\non about all varieties from quarter to\nhalf cent on packer hides, half cent to\n3i cents on country hides and a full\ncent on foreign dry hides. The\nEuropean markets are also rapidly de\nclining. prices at the Berlin auction\nsales held this week dropping about\nin per cent. Tanners are curtailing the\nworking in of hides extensively.\nFailures this week numbered -40 in\ntiie t\u2019nited States against 254 Iasi year,\nand 2U in Canada compared with 2'J\na year ago.\nSAGADAHOC\nRICHMOND.\nWin. M. Meserve and Miss Inez I..\nMerrilield were married at 7.30 F*. M.\nThursday at the home of the bride's\nparents. Mr. and Mrs. Fred S. Merri\nlield on the Post road in Bowdoinham.\nRev. A. Evans. pastor of the Ricli\nniond Free Bhptist church oHU-iating.\nThe attendanee was large. The bride\nwore l)lue nun's veiling, satin trim\nming. The bridesmaid. Miss l.eona I\nSylvester of Richmond, wore Copen\nhagen blue pongee silk. The best man\nwas Albert Merrilield. a brother of the\nbride. The ceremony was performed\nunder an arch of cvcrygreens and\ndaisies. The wedding march was play\ned by Miss Gladys Ward of Richmond.\nMisses Mabel Dinghy and Gladys\nWard assisted at the reception. The\nwedding gifts were very beautiful and\nincluded linen, cut glass and silver\nware. The bride is a member of\nProgressive (Range and the Odd\nLadies of Lewiston. The groom is the\nson of Mrs. Mary Meserve of Richmond\nand a member of Enterprise Grange.\nRoth are very popular. Among the\nout-of-town guests were Miss Hattie\nLooke of Madison; Mrs. Fred Meserve\nof Biddeford; Mrs. Martha .1. Williams\nand family of Webster. Mass.\nDR. R. D. BIBBER.\nWell-known Bath Physician Passes\nAway Thursday Night.\nBatli. Me, dune 10.- The death of\nlir. Randall Doyle Bihhe occurred\nThursday night at his home in this\ncity after an illness which has covered\nseveral years of increasing severity.\nDr. Bibber was horn in Brunswick\nSept. 1. 1X15. the son of Joint Doyle and\nMehitahle Coweii (Hall) Bibber, llis\nfather descended from Lemuel Bibber,\nwho came to this country in 16S0 and\nsettled at Dover. His maternal an\ncestor caino from England about lfi40\nand settled in Massachusetts. Dr. Bib\nber followed the sea as a young man.\nstudied medicine and graduated from\ntile Maine Medical School and settled\nin Bath, where he became prominent.\nI A widow and one son, Harold T..\nsurvive.\nBASEBALL NOTES.\n\"I he protecting arm of the National\nBaseball Commission no longer hover.\nover semi-professional baseball plav\ners Rule passed, prevented ary\nmajor or minor league from -ignim\nsemi-professional players without gain\ning teh consent of the player and com\ning to terms with the semi-profession\nal eluli management- This rule was\nrescinded Frida In a tin ling handed\ndown by the commission Friday the\nclaim of Player Richard T. Carroll,\nformer!v of the Xew York Americans,\nuof of Toronto, Eastern League, v.n:\ndisallowed. The player ill la- com\npelled to pay $H(i to the Toronto club\nJohn ft. Reilly of Brockton Friday\nwas elected captain of the Phillips-An\ndover Academy baseball team for next\nseason. He is a brother of Bernard L..\nand James Reilly of Yale, both of\nwhom were captains of Andover nines.\nThe Prix La Mariniere, $1000, distance\n11 furlongs, run at Maisons- La ffi 11 e.\nSUPERBA COFFEE 35c> Pound\n(\u00bbr<nvn by experts. Blended especially for our trade by people who know\nwhat is best in a delicious coffee.\nGOLDEN ROD COFFEE 25c a Pound\nTry it once, its delicious flavor will appeal t\u00ab\u00bb your taste, and you will be\nco